@node Connection settings
@section Connection settings

@vindex trx-host
@vindex trx-service
@vindex trx-rpc-path
@vindex trx-use-tls
@vindex trx-request-timeout
@vindex trx-rpc-auth
The following options control how @samp{trx.el} connects to the Transmission daemon.

The user option @code{trx-host} specifies the host name, IP address, or Unix socket path of the Transmission session.  Its default value is @code{"localhost"}.  If you set this to an absolute file path (e.g. @samp{"/var/run/transmission/socket"}), the connection uses a local Unix socket instead of TCP@.

The user option @code{trx-service} specifies the port number or service name.  It accepts an integer, a string, or the default value @code{9091}.  When @code{trx-host} is a socket path, this option is ignored.

The user option @code{trx-rpc-path} specifies the HTTP path to the RPC endpoint.  The default is @code{"/transmission/rpc"}.  You would change this if the daemon is behind a reverse proxy that remaps the path.

The user option @code{trx-use-tls} controls whether the connection uses TLS@.  Its default value is @code{nil}.  When set to non-nil, Emacs must have been compiled with GnuTLS support.  TLS is not used for Unix socket connections.

The user option @code{trx-request-timeout} sets the timeout in seconds for synchronous RPC requests.  The default is @code{30}.  If the daemon is slow to respond (e.g. over a high-latency network), increase this value.

The user option @code{trx-rpc-auth} holds authentication credentials for the RPC interface.  Its value is either @code{nil} (no authentication, the default) or a plist with @samp{:username} and optionally @samp{:password} keys.  If no password is provided but a username is set, @samp{trx.el} searches @code{auth-sources} using the username, @code{trx-host}, and @code{trx-service} to find one.

@node Display and formatting
@section Display and formatting

@vindex trx-units
@vindex trx-digit-delimiter
@vindex trx-time-format
@vindex trx-time-zone
The user option @code{trx-units} controls which unit system is used for displaying file sizes.  It accepts @code{nil} (the default, which uses the system default from @code{file-size-human-readable}), @code{si} for SI units (powers of 1000), or @code{iec} for IEC units (powers of 1024).  This also affects the column width of size columns in the torrent and file lists.

The user option @code{trx-digit-delimiter} specifies the character used to group digits in large numbers.  The default is @code{","} (comma).  You can set it to @code{"."} (full stop), @code{nil} (no grouping), or any other string.  Grouping is applied via @code{calc-group-char}, so numbers below 10,000 are never grouped.

The user option @code{trx-time-format} is a @code{format-time-string} format string used to display dates.  The default is @code{"%a %b %e %T %Y %z"}, producing output like @samp{Sat Apr 12 14:30:00 2026 -0300}.

The user option @code{trx-time-zone} controls the time zone for formatted dates.  Possible values are @code{nil} (local time, the default), @code{t} (UTC), @code{wall} (system wall clock), or a time zone identifier string.

@node Pieces display
@section Pieces display

@vindex trx-pieces-function
The user option @code{trx-pieces-function} determines how incomplete torrent pieces are visualized in the info buffer (@ref{Viewing torrent info}).  It accepts a function that takes a base64-encoded bitfield string and a piece count, and returns a string.  The built-in choices are:

@itemize
@item
@code{trx-format-pieces}: displays a full binary bitfield, wrapping at 72 characters per line.
@item
@code{trx-format-pieces-brief}: displays a compact one-line greyscale bar, where each character represents a group of pieces.  On terminals with 256 or more colors, it uses background colors; on fewer, it uses Unicode block characters.
@item
@code{nil}: disables pieces display entirely.
@end itemize

The default value is @code{#'trx-format-pieces}.

@node Refresh and timer
@section Refresh and timer

@vindex trx-refresh-modes
@vindex trx-refresh-interval
The user option @code{trx-refresh-modes} is a list of major modes in which buffers should automatically refresh.  When a buffer's major mode appears in this list, a timer periodically calls @code{revert-buffer}.  The available modes are @code{trx-mode}, @code{trx-files-mode}, @code{trx-info-mode}, and @code{trx-peers-mode}.  The default is an empty list, meaning no automatic refresh.  To enable live updates in the torrent list, for example:

@lisp
(setopt trx-refresh-modes '(trx-mode))
@end lisp

The user option @code{trx-refresh-interval} sets the period in seconds between automatic refreshes.  The default is @code{2}.  The value must be positive.  After five consecutive refresh failures, the timer disables itself and displays a warning.

@node Torrent guessing
@section Torrent guessing

@vindex trx-torrent-functions
@vindex trx-add-history-variable
The user option @code{trx-torrent-functions} is a list of functions used to guess a torrent source when calling @code{trx-add} interactively (@ref{Adding torrents}).  Each function takes no arguments and returns a string (a filename, URL, magnet link, or info hash) or @code{nil}.  The results are offered as defaults in the prompt.  The built-in options are:

@itemize
@item
@code{trx-ffap}: returns a file name, URL, or info hash at point, using text properties, @code{file-name-at-point-functions}, @code{thing-at-point-url-at-point}, and @code{thing-at-point}.
@item
@code{trx-ffap-selection}: applies @code{trx-ffap} to the current graphical selection.
@item
@code{trx-ffap-last-killed}: applies @code{trx-ffap} to the most recent @code{kill-ring} entry.
@end itemize

All three are enabled by default.

The user option @code{trx-add-history-variable} specifies the history list variable used by @code{trx-add} prompts.  The default is @code{trx-add-history}.  Consider adding this variable to @code{savehist-additional-variables} so that your torrent addition history persists across sessions.

@node Tracker settings
@section Tracker settings

@vindex trx-trackers
@vindex trx-tracker-history-variable
The user option @code{trx-trackers} is a list of tracker URLs offered for completion when adding or replacing trackers (@ref{Tracker management}).  It defaults to an empty list.  Populate it with your preferred trackers so they appear alongside the auto-collected announce URLs from your existing torrents.

The user option @code{trx-tracker-history-variable} specifies the history list variable used by tracker commands.  The default is @code{trx-tracker-history}.  As with @code{trx-add-history-variable}, consider adding it to @code{savehist-additional-variables}.

@node External commands and GeoIP
@section External commands and GeoIP

@vindex trx-files-command-functions
@vindex trx-geoip-function
@vindex trx-geoip-use-cache
The user option @code{trx-files-command-functions} is a list of functions used to guess default applications for running on files (@ref{Running commands on files}).  Each function accepts a list of file names and returns a list of command strings or @code{nil}.  The default includes @code{mailcap-file-default-commands}, which uses the system's MIME type database.

The user option @code{trx-geoip-function} specifies a function used to translate IP addresses into location names, shown in the ``Location'' column of the peer list (@ref{Viewing peers}).  The function should accept an IP address string and return a location name string or @code{nil}.  The built-in option @code{trx-geoiplookup} shells out to the @samp{geoiplookup} (or @samp{geoiplookup6} for IPv6) command-line tool.  The default is @code{nil}, meaning no geolocation.

The user option @code{trx-geoip-use-cache} controls whether IP-to-location results are cached in memory.  When set to non-nil, results are stored in an internal hash table, avoiding repeated lookups.  This is useful when @code{trx-geoip-function} is slow or does not have its own caching.  The default is @code{nil}.

@node Turtle mode appearance
@section Turtle mode appearance

@vindex trx-turtle-lighter
The user option @code{trx-turtle-lighter} controls the mode-line lighter text for @code{trx-turtle-mode} (@ref{Turtle mode}).  The default is @code{" turtle"}.  Alternative choices include @code{" ,=,e"} (ASCII art) and @code{" \U0001f422"} (turtle emoji).  When turtle mode is active, the lighter is appended with the current down/up speed limits.

@node Download paths
@section Download paths

@vindex trx-incomplete-dir
The user option @code{trx-incomplete-dir} specifies the directory for incomplete downloads.  When set to a directory, partially downloaded torrents are written there and moved to their final location once complete.  When nil (the default), trx leaves the daemon's existing setting alone.  This is a global Transmission session setting, not per-torrent.

Setting this option via Customize or @code{setopt} pushes the new value to the running daemon, and @code{trx-refresh-session-cache} re-pushes it whenever the daemon's stored value drifts from the option.

