@node Opening the torrent list
@section Opening the torrent list

@findex trx
The command @code{trx} is the main entry point.  It opens a @samp{*trx*} buffer in @code{trx-mode} showing all torrents in the connected Transmission session.  If the buffer already exists, it is reused.  On first invocation, it establishes a network connection to the daemon, initializes turtle mode polling, and caches session data.

Invoke it with @samp{M-x trx}.

@node Adding torrents
@section Adding torrents

@findex trx-add
The command @code{trx-add} adds a torrent to the session.  It accepts a filename, URL, magnet link, or bare 40-character info hash.  When called interactively, it uses @code{trx-torrent-functions} to guess a default from context---the file at point, the graphical selection, or the most recent kill ring entry (@ref{Torrent guessing}).

If the argument is a readable file, its contents are base64-encoded and sent as metadata.  Otherwise, the string is sent as a filename/URL@.  A bare info hash is automatically converted to a @samp{magnet:} URI@.

When the guessed default looks like a URI or magnet link, @code{trx-add} uses @code{read-string} instead of @code{read-file-name} to avoid triggering TRAMP on hostnames embedded in the link.

With a prefix argument (@samp{C-u}), the command also prompts for a target download directory.  Without the prefix, the daemon's default download directory is used.

@node Starting stopping and toggling
@section Starting, stopping, and toggling

@findex trx-toggle
The command @code{trx-toggle} toggles selected torrents between started and stopped states.  It queries the current status of the first selected torrent and sends the opposite action.  This makes it a convenient single key (@samp{s} in the torrent list) for pausing and resuming.

@node Removing and deleting torrents
@section Removing and deleting torrents

@findex trx-remove
@findex trx-delete
The command @code{trx-remove} prompts to remove selected torrents from the session.  With a prefix argument, it also deletes (unlinks) the downloaded data from disk.  The prompt clearly indicates whether data deletion is requested.

The command @code{trx-delete} is a shortcut that always deletes both the torrent and its data.  It prompts for confirmation with @code{yes-or-no-p} given the destructive nature of the operation.

Both commands clear any active marks and deactivate the region after execution.

@node Verifying torrents
@section Verifying torrents

@findex trx-verify
The command @code{trx-verify} asks Transmission to verify the integrity of selected torrents by re-checking their data against the torrent's piece hashes.  It prompts for confirmation before proceeding.

@node Moving torrents
@section Moving torrents

@findex trx-move
The command @code{trx-move} relocates selected torrents to a new directory.  It prompts for the target directory and asks for confirmation before sending the move request to the daemon.  The move is performed server-side, so the daemon must have write access to the target location.

@node Reannouncing
@section Reannouncing

@findex trx-reannounce
The command @code{trx-reannounce} forces a tracker re-announce for selected torrents.  This is useful when you want to immediately update peer information rather than waiting for the next scheduled announce cycle.

@node Setting labels
@section Setting labels

@findex trx-label
The command @code{trx-label} sets labels on selected torrents.  It prompts for label strings, offering completion from all labels currently in use across the session.  Labels are displayed alongside the torrent name in the torrent list, styled with @code{font-lock-constant-face}.

You can enter multiple labels by typing each one and pressing @samp{RET}; an empty input finishes the list.

@node Filtering the torrent list
@section Filtering the torrent list

@findex trx-filter
@findex trx-filter-clear
The command @code{trx-filter} restricts the torrent list to entries matching a filter string.  Three filter types are supported:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Plain text}: matches torrent names case-insensitively.  For example, @samp{ubuntu} shows only torrents whose names contain ``ubuntu''.
@item
@strong{Status prefix}: @samp{status:X} matches torrents whose status contains @samp{X}.  Valid statuses are @samp{stopped}, @samp{verifywait}, @samp{verifying}, @samp{downwait}, @samp{downloading}, @samp{seedwait}, and @samp{seeding}.
@item
@strong{Label prefix}: @samp{label:X} matches torrents that have a label containing @samp{X}.
@item
@strong{Negation}: prefixing any filter with @samp{!} inverts the match.  For example, @samp{!status:stopped} shows all torrents that are not stopped.
@end itemize

The filter persists across refreshes until cleared.  The command @code{trx-filter-clear} removes the active filter and shows all torrents again.  In the torrent list, @samp{/ is bound to ~trx-filter~ and =\} to @code{trx-filter-clear}.

@node Speed and ratio limits
@section Speed and ratio limits

@menu
* Global session limits::
* Per-torrent limits::
@end menu

@node Global session limits
@subsection Global session limits

@findex trx-set-download
@findex trx-set-upload
@findex trx-set-ratio
The command @code{trx-set-download} sets the global download speed limit in kB/s.  The prompt shows the current limit and whether it is enabled.  A value of zero or less disables the limit.

The command @code{trx-set-upload} does the same for the upload speed limit.

The command @code{trx-set-ratio} sets the global seed ratio limit.  A negative value disables the limit.

@node Per-torrent limits
@subsection Per-torrent limits

@findex trx-set-torrent-download
@findex trx-set-torrent-upload
@findex trx-set-torrent-ratio
@findex trx-toggle-limits
The command @code{trx-set-torrent-download} sets the download speed limit for selected torrents.  When a single torrent is selected, the prompt shows its current limit and whether it is enabled.  A value of zero or less disables the per-torrent limit.

The command @code{trx-set-torrent-upload} does the same for the upload speed limit.

The command @code{trx-set-torrent-ratio} sets the seed ratio mode and limit for selected torrents.  It first prompts for a mode---@code{session} (use the global limit), @code{torrent} (use a torrent-specific limit), or @code{unlimited}---and then, if @code{torrent} is chosen, prompts for the numeric limit.

The command @code{trx-toggle-limits} toggles whether selected torrents honor session-level speed limits.  When a torrent honors session limits, both the session and torrent limits apply; otherwise, only the torrent's own limits are enforced.

@node Bandwidth priority
@section Bandwidth priority

@findex trx-set-bandwidth-priority
The command @code{trx-set-bandwidth-priority} sets the bandwidth priority for selected torrents.  It prompts with completion for one of three levels: @code{low}, @code{normal}, or @code{high}.

@node Queue management
@section Queue management

@findex trx-queue-move-top
@findex trx-queue-move-bottom
@findex trx-queue-move-up
@findex trx-queue-move-down
Transmission maintains a download queue.  Four commands control position within it:

@itemize
@item
@code{trx-queue-move-top} moves selected torrents to the top of the queue.
@item
@code{trx-queue-move-bottom} moves them to the bottom.
@item
@code{trx-queue-move-up} moves them one position up.
@item
@code{trx-queue-move-down} moves them one position down.
@end itemize

Each command prompts for confirmation.

@node Tracker management
@section Tracker management

@findex trx-trackers-add
@findex trx-trackers-remove
@findex trx-trackers-replace
The command @code{trx-trackers-add} adds announce URLs to selected torrents.  It offers completion from @code{trx-trackers} and from all announce URLs currently in use across the session, excluding trackers already present on the selected torrent.  You can enter multiple URLs; an empty input finishes the list.

The command @code{trx-trackers-remove} removes trackers from the torrent at point.  It displays each tracker's announce URL annotated with its numeric ID@.  You can select trackers by URL or by ID@.

The command @code{trx-trackers-replace} substitutes one tracker for another on the torrent at point.  It first prompts for the tracker to replace, then for the replacement URL@.

@node Viewing torrent info
@section Viewing torrent info

@findex trx-info
The command @code{trx-info} opens a @code{trx-info-mode} buffer for the torrent at point.  The buffer displays comprehensive metadata including:

@itemize
@item
Torrent ID, name, info hash, and magnet link.
@item
Labels, download location, percent done, bandwidth priority, and queue position.
@item
Current speed with per-torrent and session limit indicators.
@item
Seed ratio and ratio mode.
@item
Error or warning messages, if any.
@item
Peer summary: connected count, uploading/downloading counts, unchoked and interested peers, and peer origin breakdown (cache, DHT, incoming, LPD, LTEP, PEX, trackers).
@item
Dates: created, added, finished, and last activity.
@item
Per-tracker statistics: announce URL, tier, peer count, seeder/leecher/download counts, last and next announce/scrape times, and any error results.
@item
Size information: wanted, downloaded, verified, corrupt, and total sizes.
@item
Piece data: count, completion percentage, piece size, and a visual representation controlled by @code{trx-pieces-function} (@ref{Pieces display}).
@end itemize

Each torrent gets its own named buffer (e.g. @samp{*trx-info: Ubuntu 24.04*}), so you can view info for multiple torrents simultaneously.  The info buffer supports key bindings for setting per-torrent limits, adding/removing trackers, setting labels, copying the magnet link, and navigating to the file list or peer list.

@node Viewing torrent files
@section Viewing torrent files

@findex trx-files
The command @code{trx-files} opens a @code{trx-files-mode} buffer for the torrent at point.  The tabulated list shows each file's completion percentage, priority (low/normal/high), wanted status, size, and name.  Files sharing a common directory prefix have the prefix stripped for readability.

In both @code{trx-files-mode} and @code{trx-info-mode} buffers, @code{default-directory} is set to the torrent's download directory.  This means that commands like @code{eshell}, @code{dired}, and @code{shell-command} automatically start in the right location.

