@node Toggling file download
@subsection Toggling file download

@findex trx-files-want
@findex trx-files-unwant
The command @code{trx-files-want} tells Transmission to download selected files.  The command @code{trx-files-unwant} tells it to skip them.  Both operate on files at point, in the active region, or marked.

@node Setting file priority
@subsection Setting file priority

@findex trx-files-priority
The command @code{trx-files-priority} sets the bandwidth priority for selected files.  It prompts with completion for @code{low}, @code{normal}, or @code{high}.

@node Visiting and opening files
@subsection Visiting and opening files

@findex trx-find-file
@findex trx-find-file-other-window
@findex trx-display-file
@findex trx-view-file
@findex trx-browse-url-of-file
@findex trx-dired-file
Several commands let you interact with downloaded files directly:

@itemize
@item
@code{trx-find-file} (@samp{RET}) visits the file at point in a read-only buffer.
@item
@code{trx-find-file-other-window} (@samp{o}) does the same in another window.
@item
@code{trx-display-file} (@samp{C-o}) displays the file in another window without selecting it.
@item
@code{trx-view-file} (@samp{v}) opens the file in View mode.
@item
@code{trx-browse-url-of-file} (@samp{W}) opens the file in a web browser.
@item
@code{trx-dired-file} (@samp{d}) opens the file's directory in Dired, with point on the file.
@end itemize

If the file does not exist at its expected path, these commands also check for a @samp{.part} suffix (a Transmission convention for incomplete files).

@node Running commands on files
@subsection Running commands on files

@findex trx-files-command
The command @code{trx-files-command} runs an external shell command on the file at point.  It uses @code{trx-files-command-functions} to suggest a default application based on the file's MIME type (@ref{External commands and GeoIP}).  The command is run asynchronously via @code{start-process}.

@node Copying and renaming files
@subsection Copying and renaming files

@findex trx-copy-file
@findex trx-rename-path
@findex trx-copy-filename-as-kill
@findex trx-copy-magnet
The command @code{trx-copy-file} copies the file at point to another location.  When @code{dired-dwim-target} is non-nil, the default target is the directory shown in the next window, mirroring Dired's behavior.

The command @code{trx-rename-path} renames a torrent file via the Transmission RPC@.  This updates the file's name within the torrent metadata, not just on disk.  After renaming, all open file-list buffers for the same torrent are automatically refreshed.

The command @code{trx-copy-filename-as-kill} copies the file name at point into the kill ring.  With a prefix argument, it copies the absolute path instead of just the base name.

The command @code{trx-copy-magnet} copies the magnet link for the current torrent to the kill ring.

@node Viewing peers
@section Viewing peers

@findex trx-peers
The command @code{trx-peers} opens a @code{trx-peers-mode} buffer for the torrent at point.  It displays a table of connected peers with columns for address, flags, progress, download rate, upload rate, client name, and location.

The flags column uses the same notation as @samp{transmission-remote(1)}; see the @uref{https://github.com/transmission/transmission/blob/main/docs/Peer-Status-Text.md, Peer Status Text} documentation for details.

The location column is populated by @code{trx-geoip-function} (@ref{External commands and GeoIP}).  If no geolocation function is configured, the column is left blank.

@node Marking items
@section Marking items

@findex trx-toggle-mark
@findex trx-unmark-all
@findex trx-invert-marks
Marks let you apply commands to multiple items at once.  Marked items are indicated with a @samp{>}  character in the left margin.

The command @code{trx-toggle-mark} (@samp{m}) toggles the mark on the item at point.  If the region is active, it toggles all items in the region.  With a numeric prefix argument, it marks that many items forward (or backward if negative).

The command @code{trx-unmark-all} (@samp{U}) removes all marks in the current buffer.

The command @code{trx-invert-marks} (@samp{t}) toggles the mark on every item, switching marked items to unmarked and vice versa.

When marks are active, commands such as @code{trx-toggle}, @code{trx-remove}, and the speed limit commands operate on all marked items.  The prompts indicate how many items are affected (e.g. @samp{[3 marked]}).

@node Turtle mode
@section Turtle mode

@findex trx-turtle-mode
@findex trx-turtle-status
@findex trx-turtle-set-speeds
@findex trx-turtle-set-days
@findex trx-turtle-set-times
Transmission's ``turtle mode'' (alternative speed limits) provides a way to throttle bandwidth during certain times.  @samp{trx.el} exposes this as the global minor mode @code{trx-turtle-mode}.

Toggling @code{trx-turtle-mode} immediately enables or disables alternative speed limits on the daemon.  When active, the mode line shows the lighter (configured by @code{trx-turtle-lighter}; see @ref{Turtle mode appearance}) followed by the current down/up limits in kB/s (e.g. @samp{turtle:500/100}).

A background polling mechanism keeps the mode-line indicator synchronized with the daemon's state and schedules.  When a turtle mode schedule changes the daemon's state (e.g. turtle mode is configured to activate on weekdays from 09:00 to 17:00), the mode line updates automatically.

The command @code{trx-turtle-status} messages a summary of the current turtle mode configuration: whether it is enabled, the speed limits, whether the schedule is enabled, the active time span, and the active days.

The command @code{trx-turtle-set-speeds} prompts for new upload and download speed limits for turtle mode.

The command @code{trx-turtle-set-days} sets which days of the week turtle mode's schedule is active.  The available day names are @code{sun}, @code{mon}, @code{tues}, @code{wed}, @code{thurs}, @code{fri}, @code{sat}, @code{weekday}, @code{weekend}, and @code{all}.  You can enter multiple days; an empty input finishes the list.  With a prefix argument, the schedule is disabled entirely.

The command @code{trx-turtle-set-times} sets the begin and end times for the turtle mode schedule.  Times are entered as human-readable strings (e.g. @samp{9:00} or @samp{5pm}) and parsed by @code{diary-entry-time}.

@node Session statistics and free space
@section Session statistics and free space

@findex trx-stats
@findex trx-free
The command @code{trx-stats} displays a summary of the Transmission session in the echo area: current download and upload rates, active and total torrent counts, total data received and sent, and session uptime.

The torrent list mode line also shows a live summary: active/total torrent count and aggregate download/upload speeds (e.g. @samp{Trx 3/10 ↓42 ↑5}).  This updates automatically when the buffer refreshes.

The command @code{trx-free} prompts for a directory and displays how much free space is available there, as reported by the Transmission daemon.

@node Daemon management
@section Daemon management

@findex trx-daemon-start
@findex trx-daemon-stop
@vindex trx-daemon-program
@vindex trx-daemon-auto-start
The command @code{trx-daemon-start} starts the Transmission daemon as a background process.  The command @code{trx-daemon-stop} sends a @samp{session-close} RPC request to shut it down gracefully.

The user option @code{trx-daemon-program} specifies the daemon executable name (default: @code{"transmission-daemon"}).

The user option @code{trx-daemon-auto-start}, when non-nil, causes @samp{trx} to automatically start the daemon when it cannot connect.  After starting the daemon, it waits briefly and retries the connection.

@node Quitting
@section Quitting

@findex trx-quit
The command @code{trx-quit} buries or closes the current Trx buffer.  If the buffer was not previously displayed in the window, it calls @code{quit-window} (which restores the previous buffer).  If the frame has only one window, it buries the buffer; otherwise, it deletes the window.

@findex trx-kill-torrent-buffers
The command @code{trx-kill-torrent-buffers} kills all per-torrent detail buffers (file lists, info buffers, and peer lists) at once, providing a quick way to clean up after a session.

@node Functions
@chapter Functions

@menu
* Torrent source detection::
* Geolocation::
* Formatting utilities::
* RPC communication::
@end menu

@node Torrent source detection
@section Torrent source detection

@findex trx-ffap
@findex trx-ffap-selection
@findex trx-ffap-last-killed
The function @code{trx-ffap} returns a file name, URL, or info hash at point.  It checks, in order: the @samp{shr-url} text property (for links in @samp{shr} buffers), the @samp{:nt-link} text property, @code{file-name-at-point-functions}, @code{thing-at-point-url-at-point}, and finally whether the word at point is a 40-character hexadecimal info hash.  It returns @code{nil} if nothing is found.

The function @code{trx-ffap-selection} applies @code{trx-ffap} to the current graphical selection (clipboard).

The function @code{trx-ffap-last-killed} applies @code{trx-ffap} to the most recent entry in @code{kill-ring}.

These functions are the defaults for @code{trx-torrent-functions} (@ref{Torrent guessing}) and can also be used in custom hooks or scripts.

@node Geolocation
@section Geolocation

@findex trx-geoiplookup
The function @code{trx-geoiplookup} translates an IP address into a country name by calling the external @samp{geoiplookup} program (or @samp{geoiplookup6} for IPv6 addresses).  It returns @code{nil} if the program is not installed.  This function is the built-in option for @code{trx-geoip-function} (@ref{External commands and GeoIP}).

@node Formatting utilities
@section Formatting utilities

@findex trx-format-pieces
@findex trx-format-pieces-brief
@findex trx-group-digits
The function @code{trx-format-pieces} renders a base64-encoded bitfield as a binary string, showing each piece as @samp{0} or @samp{1}, wrapped at 72 characters per line.  It is one of the built-in options for @code{trx-pieces-function}.

The function @code{trx-format-pieces-brief} renders a bitfield as a compact greyscale bar.  It divides the pieces into 72 groups and represents each group's completion ratio as a single character or colored space, depending on the terminal's color capabilities.

The function @code{trx-group-digits} formats a positive integer with digit grouping according to @code{trx-digit-delimiter}.  Numbers below 10,000 are returned without grouping.

@node RPC communication
@section RPC communication

@findex trx-request
@findex trx-request-async
The function @code{trx-request} sends a synchronous RPC request to the Transmission daemon and returns the parsed JSON response.  It handles session ID negotiation (409 responses), transient failures with one automatic retry, and connection pooling.  Most interactive commands use @code{trx-request-async} instead, but @code{trx-request} is available for scripting and non-interactive use.

The function @code{trx-request-async} sends an asynchronous RPC request.  Its first argument is a callback function that receives the parsed JSON response.  This is the preferred method for interactive commands, as it does not block Emacs while waiting for the daemon's reply.

@node Jackett search integration
@chapter Jackett search integration

The optional library @samp{trx-jackett.el} integrates with @uref{https://github.com/Jackett/Jackett, Jackett}, a proxy server that provides a unified search API across many torrent indexers.  It requires a running Jackett instance.

@menu
* Configuration::
* Searching::
* Working with results::
@end menu

@node Configuration
@section Configuration

@vindex trx-jackett-host
@vindex trx-jackett-port
@vindex trx-jackett-api-key
@vindex trx-jackett-use-tls
@vindex trx-jackett-categories
The user option @code{trx-jackett-host} and @code{trx-jackett-port} specify the Jackett server address (default: @code{localhost:9117}).

The user option @code{trx-jackett-api-key} is the API key for authentication.  If nil, it is resolved automatically in this order:

@enumerate
@item
Jackett's own @samp{ServerConfig.json} (checked in @samp{~/Library/Application Support/Jackett/}, @samp{~/.config/Jackett/}, and @samp{/var/lib/jackett/}).
@item
@code{auth-source-search} using the host and port (e.g. from @samp{~/.authinfo.gpg}).
@end enumerate

In most cases no configuration is needed---the key is read directly from Jackett's config file.

The user option @code{trx-jackett-categories} is a list of Torznab category IDs to filter results.  Common categories: 2000 (Movies), 3000 (Audio), 5000 (TV), 7000 (Books).  When nil, all categories are searched.

The user option @code{trx-jackett-use-tls}, when non-nil, uses HTTPS@.

@node Searching
@section Searching

@findex trx-jackett-search
The command @code{trx-jackett-search} prompts for a query, searches all configured Jackett indexers, and displays results in a @code{trx-jackett-results-mode} buffer sorted by seeders.  Columns show seeders, leechers, size, age, tracker name, category, and title.

@node Working with results
@section Working with results

@findex trx-jackett-add
@findex trx-jackett-browse-details
@findex trx-jackett-copy-magnet
@findex trx-jackett-search-again
In the results buffer:

@itemize
@item
@code{RET} (@code{trx-jackett-add}) adds the torrent at point to Transmission via its magnet link or download URL@.
@item
@code{b} (@code{trx-jackett-browse-details}) opens the torrent's details page in a web browser.
@item
@code{c} (@code{trx-jackett-copy-magnet}) copies the magnet link to the kill ring.
@item
@code{s} (@code{trx-jackett-search-again}) runs a new search.
@end itemize

Columns are sortable by clicking the header or pressing @code{S}.

@node Testing
@chapter Testing

The file @samp{trx-test.el} contains a comprehensive ERT test suite covering utility functions, formatting, data processing, HTTP/RPC response parsing, filtering, geoip caching, and constant validation.  Run the suite with:

@example
make test
@end example

Or directly:

@example
emacs --batch -l ert -l trx.el -l trx-test.el -f ert-run-tests-batch-and-exit
@end example

The tests do not require a running Transmission daemon.  They exercise all pure functions, verify HTTP status code handling with synthetic responses, and validate data structures.

